thread.title: Portland State continues a dazzling run; one of my three takeaways from the weekend
thread.title_full: Portland State continues a dazzling run; one of my three takeaways from the weekend | OregonLive.com

author: Ken Goe | The Oregonian/OregonLive
title: Portland State continues a dazzling run; one of my three takeaways from the weekend
text:
Here are my three takeaways from the weekend in college football ...
-- I don't know if Portland State has the college football team in Oregon, but the Vikings are the best local story.
Their four-day, round-trip bus trip to Saturday's game at Cal Poly San Luis Obispo produced a dramatic, 38-35 victory. It was a wild, back-and-forth game that PSU didn't clinch until a 27-yard field by Jonathan Gonzales with 33 seconds left.
The Vikings play at home this Saturday -- 2:05 p.m., Providence Park -- against traditional Big Sky powerhouse Montana. The Grizzlies usually bring a big group of fans along with them. It will be interesting to see how many PSU fans turn out for what should be critical game for the Vikings' postseason hopes.
-- The Oregon State Beavers lost their most winnable remaining game Saturday at home to Colorado, 17-13.
I actually thought the OSU defense played pretty well. But the Beavers' offense remains a work in progress. Neither Seth Collins nor Nick Mitchell looks like the kind of complete, dual-threat quarterback that coach Gary Andersen wants to have running his offense.
I think it's clear that the remainder of Oregon State's 2015 season will be more about setting the table for 2016 than anything else.
-- The Pac-12 might be the country's strongest, overall conference. But it's light at the top, and that could shut the Pac-12 out of the College Football Playoff.
It didn't help the conference's playoff hopes for Utah get blown out by USC. Now, I think Stanford probably needs to run the table if the Pac-12 is to receive one of the four berths. I don't think that will be easy.
This, of course, is one of many reasons I believe the playoff field should be expanded.
 -- Ken Goe
